{
  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustic devices to reduce human-wildlife conflict at aquaculture systems compare to their use on fishing gear?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across six studies at aquaculture systems, four studies reported reduced predation on caged salmon by grey seals, harbour seals and South American sea lions, or fewer harbour seals approaching cages, while two studies found no reductions for harbour seals or common bottlenose dolphins around fin-fish farms [2775]. On fishing gear, six studies focused on human\u2013wildlife conflict reported that five found reduced damage to fish catches and/or nets caused by common bottlenose dolphins and seals, while one found no reduction in damage to swordfish catches by California sea lions [2808]. The evidence base is larger overall for fishing gear (33 studies total on marine mammals, with six addressing conflict outcomes) than for aquaculture systems (six studies total), with mixed outcomes in both contexts [2808, 2775].",
  "action_ids": [
    "2775",
    "2808"
  ]
}

