{
  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustically reflective materials on fishing gear compare to attaching acoustically reflective objects for reducing marine mammal entanglement?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across two actions, evidence differs in strength and outcomes. For attaching acoustically reflective objects, two studies (Timor/Arafura Seas; Gulf of Alaska) found no benefits: metallic bead chains on nets did not reduce dolphin entanglements, and acrylic beads near hooks did not reduce sperm whale depredation on catches [2806]. For using acoustically reflective materials in the gear itself, five studies (Canada, Denmark, Argentina) reported mixed but partly positive results: two of three controlled studies (including two replicated) found fewer harbour porpoise entanglements in nets made with iron-oxide or barium sulfate, while one study found barium sulfate nets did not reduce dolphin entanglements; behavioural studies showed porpoises approached barium sulfate and conventional nets similarly, with fewer echolocation clicks at barium sulfate nets and similar overall echolocation activity at both net types [2807].",
  "action_ids": [
    "2806",
    "2807"
  ]
}

