{
  "query": "What are the potential negative impacts associated with using acoustic deterrent devices for marine mammal conservation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies reported behavioural changes associated with acoustic deterrent devices, including: marine mammals approaching fishing nets or lines less closely, having fewer encounters or interactions with nets, and reduced activity and sightings in surrounding areas when devices were placed on fishing gear (action 2808); dolphins avoiding a boat more frequently when devices were deployed alongside it, killer whales recorded further from a fishing vessel during device use with distances decreasing after first exposure, and reduced surfacing, echolocation, and time spent foraging or socializing by dolphins when devices were used from vessels (action 2815); reduced numbers or activity of seals, porpoises, and dolphins near moored devices, reduced echolocation activity of harbour porpoises with increasing probability of close approaches over 10\u201311 days, and reductions in seal numbers upstream of devices without reducing overall numbers (action 2816).",
