{
  "query": "How do the outcomes of using catch protection devices on longlines compare to modifying fishing pots for reducing human-wildlife conflict?",
  "relevant_summary": "Catch and hook protection devices on longlines: Across five studies, one study reported fewer unwanted catches of toothed whales when cage or chain devices were used on hooks (2821). Two of four studies (including controlled and before-and-after designs) found that net sleeves or cage/chain devices on hooks reduced damage to fish catches by sperm whales, killer whales and toothed whales, while the other two studies found that \u2018umbrella\u2019 or \u2018spider\u2019 devices did not reduce predation or damage by sperm whales or toothed whales (2821). One controlled study found streamer-based catch protection on lines reduced Indo-Pacific bottlenose and spinner dolphin bait predation, but only during the first two trials (2821). Modifying fishing pots and traps: Two controlled studies (one replicated) found that adding steel rods to lobster pots or metal frames to pots reduced the number of Australian sea lion pups or grey and harbour seals entering or becoming trapped (2822). Two controlled studies (one replicated) reported that installing wire grids or steel bars on trap-nets or bag-nets, along with strengthened netting or other access-preventing modifications, reduced damage to salmon catches by seals (2822). One controlled study showed that securing crab pot doors with a bungee cord (one of two methods) reduced common bottlenose dolphin interactions (2822). One controlled study found that wire grids on trap-nets, with strengthened netting, resulted in higher catches of undamaged salmon but not whitefish, likely due to reduced seal predation (2822).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2821",
    "2822"
  ]
}

