{
  "query": "How does the evidence for modifying fishing pots and traps to exclude mammals compare with installing exclusion or escape devices on fishing nets?",
  "relevant_summary": "Six studies assessed modifying pots/traps to exclude mammals across the North Sea (UK, Sweden), Indian River Lagoon (USA), Gulf of Finland, Bothnian Sea, Indian Ocean (Australia), and Baltic Sea; two controlled studies (one replicated) found steel rods/metal frames on pots reduced Australian sea lion pup entries and grey/harbour seal trapping, while four controlled studies reported reduced seal damage to salmon catches, reduced bottlenose dolphin interactions with one of two crab-pot door methods, and higher catches of undamaged salmon with wire grids and strengthened netting [2822]. Seven studies evaluated installing exclusion/escape devices on nets in the Indian Ocean/Tasman Sea and South Atlantic; two studies reported population-level outcomes with less than one-third of bottlenose dolphins exiting trawl escape hatches alive and fewer fur seal deaths with larger escape openings, and five studies (including controlled and before\u2013after designs) found reduced entanglements of Antarctic fur seals and bottlenose dolphins, reductions on three of four vessels after device installation, and fewer fur seal entanglements after enlarging/relocating an escape panel [2823].",
  "action_ids": [
    "2822",
    "2823"
  ]
}

