{
  "query": "What are the documented behavioral effects on marine mammals of implementing regulations for vessel operations during tourism activities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Four studies documented behavioral effects of introducing and enforcing regulations for marine and freshwater mammal watching tours: across sites in the North Atlantic (Azores), Canan\u00e9ia estuary (Brazil), South Pacific (Australia), and Bass Strait (Australia) (2838). When whale\u2011watching vessels followed approach regulations, fewer sperm whales and humpback whale pods changed behaviors (e.g., swimming speed, aerial displays) or avoided vessels compared to when regulations were not followed, while direction of movement and diving patterns/behaviors did not differ (2838). In the Canan\u00e9ia estuary, when tour boats complied with approach regulations, fewer Guiana dolphins displayed negative behaviors such as moving away, diving, or groups separating (2838). In the Bass Strait, when boats approached a seal colony to 75 m, more seals remained on shore than when boats approached to 25 m (2838). No studies were found evaluating the effects of developing and implementing general vessel\u2011operation regulations around mammals (2758) or introducing permits/licences for mammal watching tours (2839).",
